### ============================================================
### Ch6. Sane Error Handling — RFC 9457 (slides 15–16)
### ============================================================
###
### What you need before running this section:
###   1. App is running.
###   2. jwt_organizer set (only Demo 2 actually needs it — sending a
###      bad payload with a valid token to trigger validation, not auth).
###   3. jwt_attendee set for Demo 4 (DELETE while logged in as a non-
###      ORGANIZER → triggers 403, not 401).
###
### What each demo proves: every error response is
###   • status code that matches reality (404 / 400 / 401 / 403),
###   • Content-Type: application/problem+json,
###   • body shaped per RFC 9457 (type, title, status, detail, instance,
###     plus an extensions object for domain-specific data such as
###     violations[] on 400s).
###
###   1. 404 — unknown id → NotFoundExceptionMapper produces problem+json.
###   2. 400 — Bean Validation fails before the handler runs → mapper
###      collects ConstraintViolations into extensions.violations[].
###   3. 401 — no JWT on a protected POST → AuthenticationExceptionMapper
###      adds the WWW-Authenticate: Bearer header (RFC 6750 + 9457).
###   4. 403 — valid JWT, wrong role → ForbiddenExceptionMapper.
###   5. Clients that explicitly Accept: application/problem+json still
###      get the same response → mappers always serialize as problem+json.
###
### Troubleshooting:
###   • Error body is plain text or HTML → the runtime's default error
###     page is being served instead of the mapper. Confirm the mapper
###     classes are scanned (no @ApplicationPath restriction excluding
###     them) and that ApiApplication doesn't pin a getClasses() list
###     that omits them.
###   • 415 instead of 400 on Demo 2 → missing Content-Type header on
###     the POST body.
###   • 500 instead of 4xx → an unmapped exception is leaking; check the
###     server log and add/extend the corresponding ExceptionMapper.
### ============================================================

### Demo 1 — 404 Problem Details
GET http://localhost:8080/api/v1/sessions/does-not-exist
Accept: application/json

